                                        <h3 class="kicker">
                                            <span class="kicker-label"><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/pages/opinion/index.html">The Opinion Pages</a></span>                                                    <span class="pipe">|</span>                            Op-Ed Columnist                                                            </h3>
                        			<h1 itemprop="headline" id="headline" class="headline">The Best News You Don’t Know</h1>
	                                                <div id="story-meta-footer" class="story-meta-footer">
                <div class="extended-byline">
    <div class="thumb">
        <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/column/nicholas-kristof">            <img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/01/opinion/kristof-circular/kristof-circular-thumbLarge-v7.jpg" title="Nicholas Kristof" />
        </a>    </div>
    <div class="byline-meta">
                <p class="byline-column has-single-author">
                            <a class="byline-column-link" href="http://www.nytimes.com/column/nicholas-kristof">Nicholas Kristof</a>
                        <time class="dateline" datetime="2016-09-22T17:11:01-04:00" itemprop="dateModified" content="2016-09-22T17:11:01-04:00">SEPT. 22, 2016</time>
        </p>
    </div><!-- close byline-meta -->
</div><!-- close extended-byline -->
                                                
                                    <div class="story-meta-footer-sharetools">
                        <div id="sharetools-story-meta-footer" aria-label="tools" role="group" class="sharetools theme-classic  sharetools-story-meta-footer  "
data-shares="facebook,twitter,email,show-all,save"
data-url="http://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/22/opinion/the-best-news-you-dont-know.html"
data-title="The Best News You Don’t Know"
data-author="By NICHOLAS KRISTOF"
data-media="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/09/22/opinion/22kristof1web/22kristof1web-jumbo-v2.jpg"
data-description="The world is winning the war on extreme poverty."
	data-publish-date="September 22, 2016"
>
<a class="visually-hidden skip-to-text-link" href="#story-continues-1">Continue reading the main story</a>
<span class="sharetools-label visually-hidden">Share This Page</span>
<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad hidden nocontent robots-nocontent">
<a class="visually-hidden skip-to-text-link" href="#story-continues-1">Continue reading the main story</a>
</div>
</div><!-- close shareTools -->
                                                    <button class="button comments-button  theme-speech-bubble" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
                                            </div>
                            </div><!-- close story-meta-footer -->
        </div><!-- close story-meta -->
    </header>

    <script type="text/javascript">
        if (
            window.magnum
            && window.magnum.getFlags().indexOf('headlineBalancer') > 0
            && window.magnum.headlineBalancer
            && window.magnum.headlineBalancer.initialize
            && window.magnum.headlineBalancer.shouldRun()
        ) {
            window.magnum.headlineBalancer.initialize();
        }
    </script>

        
    <div class="story-body-supplemental">
    <div class="story-body story-body-1">
        <figure id="media-100000004662654" class="media photo lede layout-large-horizontal" data-media-action="modal" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/09/22/opinion/22kristof1web/22kristof1web-master768-v2.jpg" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject" aria-label="media" role="group">
    <span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
    <div class="image">
            <img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/09/22/opinion/22kristof1web/22kristof1web-master768-v2.jpg" alt="" class="media-viewer-candidate" data-mediaviewer-src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/09/22/opinion/22kristof1web/22kristof1web-superJumbo-v2.jpg" data-mediaviewer-caption="A schoolgirl in Nairobi, Kenya." data-mediaviewer-credit="Tobin Jones/Agence France-Presse &mdash; Getty Images"  itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/09/22/opinion/22kristof1web/22kristof1web-master768-v2.jpg"/>
            <meta itemprop="height" content="511" />
            <meta itemprop="width" content="768" />
    </div>
        <figcaption class="caption" itemprop="caption description">
                <span class="caption-text">A schoolgirl in Nairobi, Kenya.</span>
                        <span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder">
            <span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span>
            Tobin Jones/Agence France-Presse — Getty Images        </span>
            </figcaption>
    </figure>
<p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="175" data-total-count="175"><em>The world is a mess, with billions of people locked in inescapable cycles of war, famine and poverty, with more children than ever perishing from hunger, disease and violence.</em></p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="229" data-total-count="404">That’s about the only thing Americans agree on; we’re polarized about all else. But several polls have found that about 9 out of 10 Americans believe that global poverty has worsened or stayed the same over the last 20 years.</p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="60" data-total-count="464">Fortunately, the one point Americans agree on is dead wrong.</p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="461" data-total-count="925">As world leaders gather for the United Nations General Assembly this week, all the evidence suggests that we are at an inflection point for the ages. The number of people living in extreme poverty ($1.90 per person per day) has <a href="https://ourworldindata.org/world-poverty/">tumbled</a> by half in two decades, and the number of small children dying has dropped by a similar proportion — that’s six million lives a year saved by vaccines, breast-feeding promotion, pneumonia medicine and diarrhea treatments!</p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="144" data-total-count="1069">Historians may conclude that the most important thing going on in the world in the early 21st century was a stunning decline in human suffering.</p><figure id="media-100000004662600" class="media photo embedded layout-small-horizontal media-100000004662600 ratio-tall" data-media-action="modal" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/09/22/opinion/22kristof2web/22kristof2web-master315-v2.jpg" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject" aria-label="media" role="group">
    <span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
    <div class="image">
            <img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/09/22/opinion/22kristof2web/22kristof2web-master315-v2.jpg" alt="" class="media-viewer-candidate" data-mediaviewer-src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/09/22/opinion/22kristof2web/22kristof2web-superJumbo-v2.jpg" data-mediaviewer-caption="A crowded train in Mumbai, India." data-mediaviewer-credit="Rajanish Kakade/Associated Press"  itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/09/22/opinion/22kristof2web/22kristof2web-master315-v2.jpg"/>
            <meta itemprop="height" content="212" />
            <meta itemprop="width" content="315" />
    </div>
        <figcaption class="caption" itemprop="caption description">
                <span class="caption-text">A crowded train in Mumbai, India.</span>
                        <span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder">
            <span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span>
            Rajanish Kakade/Associated Press        </span>
            </figcaption>
    </figure>
<p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="126" data-total-count="1195">O.K., you’re thinking that I’ve finally cracked up after spending too much time in desperate places. So a few data points:</p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="315" data-total-count="1510">■ As recently as 1981, when I was finishing college, 44 percent of the world’s population lived in <a href="http://www.worldbank.org/en/topic/poverty/overview">extreme poverty</a>, according to the World Bank. Now the share is believed to be less than <a href="http://www.worldbank.org/en/news/press-release/2015/10/04/world-bank-forecasts-global-poverty-to-fall-below-10-for-first-time-major-hurdles-remain-in-goal-to-end-poverty-by-2030">10 percent</a> and falling. “This is the best story in the world today,” says Jim Yong Kim, the president of the World Bank.</p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="175" data-total-count="1685">■ For the entire history of the human species until the 1960s, a majority of adults were illiterate. Now 85 percent of adults worldwide are literate and the share is rising.</p><div id="story-ad-1" class="story-ad ad ad-placeholder nocontent robots-nocontent">
    <div class="accessibility-ad-header visually-hidden">
    <p>Advertisement</p>
</div>
<a class="visually-hidden skip-to-text-link" href="#story-continues-1">Continue reading the main story</a>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="190" data-total-count="1875" id="story-continues-1">■ Although inequality has risen in America, the global trend is more encouraging: Internationally, inequality is on the decline because of gains by the poor in places like China and India.</p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="311" data-total-count="2186">The U.N. aims to <a href="https://sustainabledevelopment.un.org/sdg1">eradicate</a> extreme poverty by 2030, and experts believe it is possible to get <a href="https://www.usaid.gov/sites/default/files/documents/1870/USAID-Extreme-Poverty-Discussion-Paper.pdf">quite close</a>. In short, on our watch, we have a decent chance of virtually wiping out ills that have plagued humanity for thousands of generations, from illiteracy to the most devastating kind of hand-to-mouth poverty.</p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="246" data-total-count="2432">Yet the public thinks the opposite, that poverty is getting worse. <a href="http://www.glocalities.com/news/poverty.html">A poll</a> to be released Thursday by Motivaction, a Dutch firm, finds that only 1 percent of Americans surveyed realized that global extreme poverty had fallen by half over 20 years.</p><div class="newsletter-signup hidden original-newsletter-module dropzone-10 ab-test-newsletter-buffet" id="newsletter-promo" data-newsletter-productCode="NK"  data-newsletter-productTitle="Nicholas Kristof">
    <div class="single-newsletter-promo" data-newsletter-productCode="NK">
        <h2 class="headline">Sign Up for the Nicholas Kristof Newsletter</h2>        <p class="summary">Receive emails about each column and other occasional commentary.</p>    </div>
